<Layout title="Judson Ch.8 — Lattices and Boolean Algebras" favicon="🔗">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/abstract-algebra/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to algebra</a>

    <h1>Lattices and Boolean Algebras</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Tom Judson &middot; GFDL &middot; <a href="http://abstract.ups.edu/">Abstract Algebra: Theory and Applications, Ch. 8</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>lattice</strong> is a partially ordered set where every pair of elements has a least upper bound (join) and a greatest lower bound (meet). A <strong>Boolean algebra</strong> is a distributive, complemented lattice. Boolean algebras connect algebra to logic: meet is AND, join is OR, complement is NOT.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Partial orders -->
    <h3>Partial orders</h3>
    <p>A <strong>partial order</strong> is a relation that is reflexive (a &le; a), antisymmetric (a &le; b and b &le; a implies a = b), and transitive (a &le; b and b &le; c implies a &le; c). Not every pair needs to be comparable. The divisibility relation on positive integers is a partial order: 2 | 6 but 2 and 3 are incomparable.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Divisibility as a partial order on divisors of 12
; a <= b means a divides b

(define (divides? a b) (= 0 (modulo b a)))

(define divs '(1 2 3 4 6 12))

(display "Divisibility on [1,2,3,4,6,12]:") (newline)
(for-each
  (lambda (a)
    (display "  ") (display a) (display " divides: ")
    (for-each
      (lambda (b)
        (when (and (not (= a b)) (divides? a b))
          (display b) (display " ")))
      divs)
    (newline))
  divs)
; 2 and 3 are incomparable: neither divides the other.
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Divisibility partial order on divisors of 12
divs = [1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12]
for a in divs:
    above = [b for b in divs if b != a and b % a == 0]
    print(str(a).rjust(2) + " divides: " + str(above))
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Meet and join -->
    <h3>Meet and join</h3>
    <p>The <strong>meet</strong> (greatest lower bound) of a and b, written a &and; b, is the largest element below both. The <strong>join</strong> (least upper bound), written a &or; b, is the smallest element above both. In the divisibility lattice, meet is GCD and join is LCM.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Meet = GCD, Join = LCM in the divisibility lattice

(define (gcd a b)
  (if (= b 0) a (gcd b (modulo a b))))

(define (lcm a b)
  (/ (* a b) (gcd a b)))

(display "meet(4, 6) = gcd(4, 6) = ") (display (gcd 4 6)) (newline)
(display "join(4, 6) = lcm(4, 6) = ") (display (lcm 4 6)) (newline)

(display "meet(2, 3) = gcd(2, 3) = ") (display (gcd 2 3)) (newline)
(display "join(2, 3) = lcm(2, 3) = ") (display (lcm 2 3)) (newline)

; Properties: a ^ b <= a, a ^ b <= b
;             a <= a v b, b <= a v b
(display "4 ^ 6 = 2 divides both 4 and 6? ")
(display (and (= 0 (modulo 4 (gcd 4 6)))
              (= 0 (modulo 6 (gcd 4 6)))))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Meet = GCD, Join = LCM
from math import gcd
lcm = lambda a, b: a * b // gcd(a, b)

print("meet(4,6) = gcd = " + str(gcd(4,6)))
print("join(4,6) = lcm = " + str(lcm(4,6)))
print("meet(2,3) = gcd = " + str(gcd(2,3)))
print("join(2,3) = lcm = " + str(lcm(2,3)))
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- SVG: diamond lattice -->
    <h3>The diamond lattice</h3>
    <p>The divisors of 6 under divisibility form a diamond-shaped lattice. This is the simplest non-chain lattice: 2 and 3 are incomparable, but both sit between 1 and 6.</p>

    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
